       Report Timing- Column List Options

       Option Description

       adjustment
              Reports  generated  clock  adjustment values. When reporting the
              detailed path for a generated  clock,  there  are  circumstances
              where the arrival time needs to be adjusted when a create_gener-
              ated_clock  assertion is encountered along the path. The adjust-
              ment argument can be used to provide a clearer indication of why
              a "jump" in the arrival time is seen in the path report.

              When the create_generated_clock -edge_shift parameter is  speci-
              fied, the adjustment column will show the amount of shift speci-
              fied.

              abs_delay_err"  Reports  the absolute delay difference of Tempus
              from Spice.

              abs_slew_err" Reports the absolute  slew  difference  of  Tempus
              from Spice.

       annotation
              Reports RC parasitic annotations for net arcs, and delay annota-
              tions for either gate or net arcs. The following annotations are
              reported:

              * SDF:  SDF  back-annotation. The annotation status reflects the
                gate arc, not the interconnect arc.

              * SPEF: This entry appears if parasitic extraction has been done
                or annotated using SPEF.

              * LumpedRC: Lumped RC annotation

              * DlyAssert: Assertion set with set_annotated_delay command

              * WLM: Wire load model back-annotation

              * <none>: All others

              aocv_adj_stages" Shows up "Aocv Adjust Stages" column. This col-
              umn reports the AOCV adjustment stages that indicate  the  total
              effective stage count.

       aocv_derate
              Reports the graph-based AOCV derating factor used for cells/nets
              in  AOCV  mode.  In  retime mode, this column will report graph-
              based derating for cells/nets before the AOCV branch  point  and
              path-based derating.

              aocv_weight" Reports AOCV weight values for the path elements.

       arc    Reports  the arc as described by the from pin, from pin edge, to
              pin, and to pin edge. For example, the arc from the rising  edge
              of pin A to the falling edge of pin Z is reported as A -> Z.

       arrival
              Reports the arrival time on the pin.

              arrival_mean" Reports mean of the arrival time on a pin.

              arrival_sigma" Reports standard deviation of the arrival time on
              a pin.

       cell   Reports the cell name of the given pin's instance.

       delay  Reports the arc delay. If the stolen slack at the arc output pin
              (output  of  transparent latches) is not zero, the stolen column
              is also displayed along with this column.

              delay_mean" Reports the mean of each arc's delay.

              delay_sigma " Reports the standard deviation of each  arc's  de-
              lay.

              Note:  In  the absence of correlated and uncorrelated components
              of variation, the individual delay  sigma  values  will  not  be
              summed up.

       direction
              Reports the pin direction (IN, OUT).

       edge   Reports the edge of a pin (^=R, v=F).

       fanin  Reports  the number of source nodes of a net connected to a tim-
              ing pin.

       fanout Reports the number of sinks of a net connected to a timing pin.

              flags" Indicates the size_only, dont_use, dont_touch, and  ideal
              attributes.

              When  the 'flags' option is specified, a capacitance group entry
              (if it exists) will be displayed under the "Flags" column.  This
              value indicates the input capacitance group being used for delay
              calculations - C1C2 (2-piece model) or C1CN (n-piece model).

       hpin   Reports the hierarchical name for a given pin.

              Note: The hpin, pin, and timing_point will print the same values
              in the report output.

       incr_delay
              Reports  the incremental delay of a pertaining arc. The software
              reads the incremental delay from an incremental SDF  file  using
              the read_sdf command.

       instance
              Reports the hierarchical name of a given pin's instance.

       instance_location
              Reports  the  location  (x,y) of an instance. If a design is not
              placed, this column will be blank. This option displays the  in-
              stance column automatically.

              latch_window"  Reports  the available window for latch to sample
              the data.

       load   Reports the total capacitance load on a given pin.

              module" Reports the module name of the corresponding block hier-
              archy. This hierarchical module name will be reported only  when
              the -hpin parameter of the report_timing command is specified.

       net    Reports the hierarchical name of a net connected to a given pin.

              pct_delay_err"  Reports  the  percent delay difference of Tempus
              from Spice.

              pct_slew_err" Reports the percent slew difference of Tempus from
              Spice.

       phase  Reports the phase name of a pin.

              phys_info " Shows minimum/maximum assigned  layer,  and  non-de-
              fault rule name information.

       pin    Reports the reference name for the given pin.

       pin_load
              Reports the pin load data. The pin load refers to the sum of pin
              capacitance of all the pins connected to the current net.

       pin_location
              Reports  the location (x,y) of a pin. If a design is not placed,
              this column will be blank.

       power_domain
              Reports power domain details of the specified path instance.

       required
              Reports the required time on a pin.

       retime_delay
              Reports the recalculated arc delay based on the path being rean-
              alyzed with the specified retime method.

              retime_delay_mean" Reports the mean of the recalculated arc  de-
              lay  on  the  path  being  reanalyzed  with the specified retime
              method.

       retime_mis_delta
              Reports MIS delta delay in PBA mode for MIS-aware timing arcs in
              the path.

       retime_delay_sigma
              Reports the standard deviation of each parameter of an arc's re-
              timed delay.

       retime_slew
              Reports the recalculated slew based on the path being reanalyzed
              with the specified retime method.

              retime_slew_mean" Reports the mean of each parameter of  an  arc
              sink pin's retimed slew.

       retime_slew_sigma
              Reports  the standard deviation of each parameter of an arc sink
              pin's retimed slew.

       stage_count
              Displays the aggregate stage count of  a  specific  instance  in
              graph-based  analysis  (GBA) mode, and the actual stage count in
              path-based analysis (PBA) mode.

              slew" Reports the propagated slew at the given pin.

              slew_mean" Reports mean of each parameter of an arc  sink  pin's
              slew.

              slew_sigma"  Reports the standard deviation of each parameter of
              an arc sink pin's slew.

              socv_derate" Reports the SOCV or the spatial derating factor ap-
              plied on the cells or nets in SOCV analysis mode.

              spice_arrival" Reports the Spice  arrival  time  at  the  timing
              point.

              spice_delay" Reports the Spice delay of a timing arc.

              spice_slew" Reports the Spice slew of a timing point.

       stolen Reports  the  slack  stolen  (or  the time given to the previous
              stage) at the given pin. If the slack is not zero and the  delay
              column  is  specified,  then this column is displayed by default
              (but only visible on the output of transparent latches).

       timing_point
              Reports the hierarchical names for the given points.

              total_derate" Reports the total derating factor applied  on  the
              corresponding  cell  or nets that reflect the combined impact of
              all the derates (OCV/AOCV/spatial) applied on each stage of  the
              timing path.

              Note:  By default, the software will take into account the nega-
              tive delays and keep the SOCV derate column  in  sync  with  the
              user-derate  column.  The software multiplies the negative delay
              by (2.0 - derating factor) to make it more pessimistic. However,
              reporting will always show derates based on the positive  delay.
              The  timing  report output will show similar values for the SOCV
              Derate and Total Derate columns, but there will be no changes in
              the slack values.

       user_derate
              Reports the derating scale factors set with the  set_timing_der-
              ate command.

              Note: The timing system cannot provide an accurate derating fac-
              tor  for the lumped gate and wire delay when the set_timing_der-
              ate factors for -cell_delay and -net_delay are  not  equivalent.
              In this case, an asterisk (*) is reported in the SSI Derate col-
              umn.

              voltage"  Returns the voltage that is used during delay calcula-
              tions.

              vt_skew_derate" Returns voltage threshold (VT) skew analysis de-
              tails.

       when_cond
              Reports the "when" condition of the arc  specified  in  the  li-
              brary.

       wire_load
              Reports the wire load.

              wlmodel"  Reports  the  kind  of parasitic used by a pin or net,
              such as SPEF. If the wire load model is derived from  a  Liberty
              file, the information is reported in the following format:

              Wireload model (.lib <model_name> <library_name>)

Reporting Timing Checks Between Various Types of Clocks
       The  following table summarizes the timing checks and the min/max delay
       checks that are performed based on the types of launching and capturing
       clocks:

              * NZ (Non Zero Period Clock - Regular Clock)

              * Z (Zero Period Clock - Regular clock whose period is equal  to
                zero)

              * @ (Asynchronous Clock - Clock which triggers the default input
                delay and the input delay without a clock)

              * CPD (Combinational Path Delay)

       ________________________________________________________

       | Launching  |  Capturing  |  Timing     |  Path       |

       | Clock      |  Clock      |   Checks    |   Delay     |

       |            |             |             |   Checks    |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  @         |   @         |   NO        |   CPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  Z         |   @         |   NO        |   CPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  NZ        |   @         |   NO        |   CPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  @         |   Z         |   YES       |   SPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  @         |   NZ        |   YES       |   SPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  NZ        |   Z         |   NO        |   SPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  Z         |   NZ        |   YES       |   SPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  Z         |   Z         |   YES       |   SPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

       |  NZ        |   NZ        |   YES       |   SPD       |

       |____________|_____________|_____________|_____________|

SPD (Sequential Path Delay) Examples
